body:
Hi there!

I think I found an issue in Verilator. When trying to verilate the source below against a simple C++ testbench, I get this error:

```
%Error: /path/to/top.sv:14:125: Value too wide for 32-bits expected in this context 98'h3ffffffffffffffffffffffff
   14 |   assign { _03_[97:88], out_data[63:32], _03_[55:0] } = { _01_, in_data, _05_[0] } >> { _04_[97:94], _02_, _04_[92:76], _01_, _04_[74:0] };
      |                                                                                                                             ^
%Error: Exiting due to 1 error(s)
```

top.sv:
```
module top(in_data, out_data);
  wire _00_;
  wire _01_;
  wire _02_;
  wire [97:0] _03_;
  wire [97:0] _04_;
  wire [97:0] _05_;
  wire [218:0] _06_;
  input [95:0] in_data;
  wire [95:0] in_data;
  output [95:0] out_data;
  wire [95:0] out_data;
  assign _00_ = _02_ | ~(_01_);
  assign { _03_[97:88], out_data[63:32], _03_[55:0] } = { _01_, in_data, _05_[0] } >> { _04_[97:94], _02_, _04_[92:76], _01_, _04_[74:0] };
  assign { _06_[218:136], _04_[97:94], _02_, _04_[92:76], _01_, _04_[74:0], _06_[37:0] } = { in_data[46:20], in_data, in_data } ~^ { in_data[90:64], in_data, in_data };
  assign out_data[0] = ~((in_data[52] & _05_[0]) | _00_);
  assign _05_[0] = ~((in_data[24] & in_data[16]) | (in_data[16] & in_data[42]));
  assign _03_[87:56] = out_data[63:32];
  assign { _04_[93], _04_[75] } = { _02_, _01_ };
  assign _05_[97:1] = { _01_, in_data };
  assign _06_[135:38] = { _04_[97:94], _02_, _04_[92:76], _01_, _04_[74:0] };
endmodule
```

Interestingly,
- Changing `>> { _04_[97:94], _02_, _04_[92:76], _01_, _04_[74:0] }` with `_04_` moves the error to the next line.
- Changing it with `_05_` removes the error.

I'm using `Verilator 5.018 2023-10-30 rev v5.004-74-g41e5f6b7d` on Ubuntu 20.04.

Thanks!

EDIT: Another design exhibiting the same problem is:

```
module top(in_data, out_data);
  wire [106:0] _0_;
  wire [106:0] _1_;
  wire [248:0] _2_;
  input [95:0] in_data;
  wire [95:0] in_data;
  output [95:0] out_data;
  wire [95:0] out_data;
  assign { _0_[106:83], out_data[31:0], _0_[50:0] } = { in_data[41:31], in_data } >> _1_;
  assign { _2_[248:129], out_data[32], _2_[127:107], _1_ } = { in_data[73:17], in_data, in_data } ~^ { in_data[93:37], in_data, in_data };
  assign _0_[82:51] = out_data[31:0];
  assign { _2_[128], _2_[106:0] } = { out_data[32], _1_ };
endmodule
```
